711038f-a.text:
10th Street, west from Fifth Avenue, showing 10-44 West 10th Street on the south side. 26 West 10th Street, in the middle of the group of brownstone houses with the second story balcony common to them all, is the residence of the columnist "F. P. A." (Franklin P. Adams). 44 West 10th Street is The John Alcen, a 9-story apartment house erected between 1916 and 1920 on the site of old 42-6, brick houses. Prior to the 1870's this street was numbered east from Sixth Avenue.
May 29, 1933
P. L. Sperr.
No. 14, the second house from the left, in which Mark Twain lived when he returned from his world tour in 1901, has been sold by Francis S. Farr and the new owner will remodel[l] same, according to the New York Times of April 19, 1938. It is said that during this residence, the author wrote "To the Person sitting in Darkness," ["]The Tale of a King and his Treasure" and "The Watermelons."

711039f-a.text:
10th Street, north side, west from and including Fifth Avenue, showing the Church of the Ascension on the N.W. corner. This was erected in 1850 by the Protestant Episcopal Church; this congregation moved here from its first location, in Prince Street (1839-50).
June 11, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

711040f-a.text:
West 10th Street, southside, west from (No. 18, left) a point to the west of Fifth Avenue. The photographer is viewing towards Sixth Avenue to show a row of balconaded buildings bearing Nos. 20 to 38 inclusive and situated in the middle of this block. No. 26, reputed to have been the home of President Martin Van Buren, has recently been leased by Franklin P. Adams (F. P. A. of news fame) for alteration into modern one room
apartments.
une 15, 1938.
P. L. Sperr,

Fifth Avenue, southeastward from a point above 10th Street to show prominently the modern apartment building known as No.1 Fifth Avenue.  To the right beneath the flags is the Washington Arch.  The photographer shows in the foreground the railing outside of the Church of the Ascension which occupys (sic) the plot at the N.W. corner of the Avenue and W. 10th Street.

June 15, 1938

F.L. Sperr
